<p>The <b>sievert</b> (symbol: <b>Sv</b><sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-1"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>note 1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span>=
</a></sup>) is a derived unit in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/International_System_of_Units" title=3D"International System of Units">I=
nternational System of Units</a> (SI) intended to represent the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic" title=3D"Stochastic">stochastic</=
a> health risk of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ionizing_radiati=
on" title=3D"Ionizing radiation">ionizing radiation</a>, which is defined a=
s the probability of causing radiation-induced cancer and genetic damage. T=
he sievert is important in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dosimet=
ry" title=3D"Dosimetry">dosimetry</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Radiation_protection" title=3D"Radiation protection">radiation prot=
ection</a>. It is named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolf=
_Maximilian_Sievert" title=3D"Rolf Maximilian Sievert">Rolf Maximilian Siev=
ert</a>, a Swedish medical physicist renowned for work on radiation dose me=
asurement and research into the biological effects of radiation.
</p><p>The sievert unit is used for radiation dose quantities such as <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalent_dose" title=3D"Equivalent do=
se">equivalent dose</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effect=
ive_dose_(radiation)" title=3D"Effective dose (radiation)">effective dose</=
a>, which represent the risk of external radiation from sources outside the=
 body, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Committed_dose" title=
=3D"Committed dose">committed dose</a>, which represents the risk of intern=
al irradiation due to inhaled or ingested radioactive substances. According=
 to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Commission_o=
n_Radiological_Protection" title=3D"International Commission on Radiologica=
l Protection">International Commission on Radiological Protection</a> (ICRP=
), one sievert results in a 5.5% <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
robability" title=3D"Probability">probability</a> of eventually developing =
fatal cancer based on the disputed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Linear_no-threshold_model" title=3D"Linear no-threshold model">linear no-t=
hreshold model</a> of ionizing radiation exposure.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ICRP1=
03_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siever=
t#cite_note-ICRP103-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-3"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>To calculate the value of stochastic health risk in sieverts, the ph=
ysical quantity <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absorbed_dose" tit=
le=3D"Absorbed dose">absorbed dose</a> is converted into equivalent dose an=
d effective dose by applying factors for radiation type and biological cont=
ext, published by the ICRP and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/International_Commission_on_Radiation_Units_and_Measurements" title=3D"Int=
ernational Commission on Radiation Units and Measurements">International Co=
mmission on Radiation Units and Measurements</a> (ICRU).  One sievert equal=
s 100 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roentgen_equivalent_man" tit=
le=3D"Roentgen equivalent man">rem</a>, which is an older, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Centimetre%E2%80%93gram%E2%80%93second_system_of_u=
nits" title=3D"Centimetre=E2=80=93gram=E2=80=93second system of units">CGS<=
/a> radiation unit.=20
</p><p>Conventionally, deterministic health effects due to acute tissue dam=
age that is certain to happen, produced by high dose rates of radiation, ar=
e compared to the physical quantity absorbed dose measured by the unit <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gray_(unit)" title=3D"Gray (unit)">gra=
y</a> (Gy).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSievert&amp;acti=
on=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>edit</s=
pan></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"CIPM_definition_of_the_siev=
ert">CIPM definition of the sievert</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D=
"Edit section: CIPM definition of the sievert"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The SI definition given by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
CIPM" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"CIPM">International Committee for Weig=
hts and Measures (CIPM)</a> says:
</p><p>"The quantity dose equivalent <i>H</i> is the product of the absorbe=
d dose <i>D</i> of ionizing radiation and the dimensionless factor <i>Q</i>=
 (quality factor) defined as a function of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Linear_energy_transfer" title=3D"Linear energy transfer">linear en=
ergy transfer</a> by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internati=
onal_Commission_on_Radiation_Units_and_Measurements" title=3D"International=
 Commission on Radiation Units and Measurements">ICRU</a>"
</p>
<dl><dd><i>H</i> =3D <i>Q</i> =C3=97 <i>D</i><sup id=3D"cite_ref-CIPM,_2002=
:_Recommendation_2_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-CIPM,_2002:_Recommendation_2-5"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd>=
</dl>
<p>The value of <i>Q</i> is not defined further by CIPM, but it requires th=
e use of the relevant ICRU recommendations to provide this value.
</p><p>The CIPM also says that "in order to avoid any risk of confusion bet=
ween the absorbed dose <i>D</i> and the dose equivalent <i>H</i>, the speci=
al names for the respective units should be used, that is, the name gray sh=
ould be used instead of joules per kilogram for the unit of absorbed dose <=
i>D</i> and the name sievert instead of joules per kilogram for the unit of=
 dose equivalent <i>H</i>".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-CIPM,_2002:_Recommendation_2=
_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#=
cite_note-CIPM,_2002:_Recommendation_2-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In summary:
</p>
<dl><dd><b>gray</b>: quantity <i>D</i>=E2=80=94absorbed dose
<dl><dd>1&nbsp;Gy =3D 1&nbsp;joule/kilogram=E2=80=94a physical quantity. 1&=
nbsp;Gy is the deposit of a joule of radiation energy per kilogram of matte=
r or tissue.</dd></dl></dd></dl>
<dl><dd><b>sievert</b>: quantity <i>H</i>=E2=80=94equivalent dose
<dl><dd>1&nbsp;Sv =3D 1&nbsp;joule/kilogram=E2=80=94a biological effect. Th=
e sievert represents the equivalent biological effect of the deposit of a j=
oule of radiation energy in a kilogram of human tissue. The ratio to absorb=
ed dose is denoted by <i>Q</i>.</dd></dl></dd></dl>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"ICRP_definition_of_the_siev=
ert">ICRP definition of the sievert</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/w/index.php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D=
"Edit section: ICRP definition of the sievert"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The ICRP definition of the sievert is:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ICRP_publicati=
on_103_-_Glossary_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-ICRP_publication_103_-_Glossary-6"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd>"The sievert is the special name for the SI unit of equivalent dose=
, effective dose, and operational dose quantities. The unit is joule per ki=
logram."</dd></dl>
<p>The sievert is used for a number of dose quantities which are described =
in this article and are part of the international radiological protection s=
ystem devised and defined by the ICRP and ICRU.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"External_dose_quantities">E=
xternal dose quantities</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: External dose quantities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Dose_quantities_and_units.png" class=3D"mw-fi=
le-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/=
thumb/9/96/Dose_quantities_and_units.png/500px-Dose_quantities_and_units.pn=
g" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"450" height=3D"251" class=3D"mw-file-element=
" data-file-width=3D"1222" data-file-height=3D"681"></a><figcaption>Externa=
l radiation dose quantities used in radiological protection</figcaption></f=
igure>
<p>When the sievert is used to represent the stochastic effects of external=
 ionizing radiation on human tissue, the radiation doses received are measu=
red in practice by radiometric instruments and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Dosimeters" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Dosimeters">dosimet=
ers</a> and are called operational quantities. To relate these actual recei=
ved doses to likely health effects, protection quantities have been develop=
ed to predict the likely health effects using the results of large epidemio=
logical studies. Consequently, this has required the creation of a number o=
f different dose quantities within a coherent system developed by the ICRU =
working with the ICRP.
</p><p>The external dose quantities and their relationships are shown in th=
e accompanying diagram. The ICRU is primarily responsible for the operation=
al dose quantities, based upon the application of ionising radiation metrol=
ogy, and the ICRP is primarily responsible for the protection quantities, b=
ased upon modelling of dose uptake and biological sensitivity of the human =
body.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Naming_conventions">Naming =
conventions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Sievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Naming co=
nventions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</s=
pan></span></div>
<p>The ICRU/ICRP dose quantities have specific purposes and meanings, but s=
ome use common words in a different order. There can be confusion between, =
for instance, <i>equivalent dose</i> and <i>dose equivalent</i>.
</p><p>Although the CIPM definition states that the linear energy transfer =
function (Q) of the ICRU is used in calculating the biological effect, the =
ICRP in 1990<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> developed the "protect=
ion" dose quantities <i>effective</i> and <i>equivalent</i> dose which are =
calculated from more complex computational models and are distinguished by =
not having the phrase <i>dose equivalent</i> in their name. Only the operat=
ional dose quantities which still use Q for calculation retain the phrase <=
i>dose equivalent</i>. However, there are joint ICRU/ICRP proposals to simp=
lify this system by changes to the operational dose definitions to harmonis=
e with those of protection quantities. These were outlined at the 3rd Inter=
national Symposium on Radiological Protection in October 2015, and if imple=
mented would make the naming of operational quantities more logical by intr=
oducing "dose to lens of eye" and "dose to local skin" as <i>equivalent dos=
es</i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-endo_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-endo-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States" title=
=3D"United States">USA</a> there are differently named dose quantities whic=
h are not part of the ICRP nomenclature.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-9"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Physical_quantities">Physic=
al quantities</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Physic=
al quantities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>These are directly measurable physical quantities in which no allowance =
has been made for biological effects. Radiation <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Fluence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fluence">fluence</a> =
is the number of radiation particles impinging per unit area per unit time,=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kerma_(physics)" title=3D"Kerma (=
physics)">kerma</a> is the ionising effect on air of <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_rays" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gamma rays">g=
amma rays</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X-rays" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"X-rays">X-rays</a> and is used for instrument calibr=
ation, and absorbed dose is the amount of radiation energy deposited per un=
it mass in the matter or tissue under consideration.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Operational_quantities">Ope=
rational quantities</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: O=
perational quantities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Operational quantities are measured in practice, and are the means of di=
rectly measuring dose uptake due to exposure, or predicting dose uptake in =
a measured environment. In this way they are used for practical dose contro=
l, by providing an estimate or upper limit for the value of the protection =
quantities related to an exposure. They are also used in practical regulati=
ons and guidance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The calibration of individual and area dosimeters in photon fields i=
s performed by measuring the collision "air kerma free in air" under condit=
ions of secondary electron equilibrium. Then the appropriate operational qu=
antity is derived applying a conversion coefficient that relates the air ke=
rma to the appropriate operational quantity. The conversion coefficients fo=
r photon radiation are published by the ICRU.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-11" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-1=
1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p><p>Simple (non-anthropomorphic) "phantoms" are used to relate operation=
al quantities to measured free-air irradiation. The ICRU sphere phantom is =
based on the definition of an ICRU 4-element tissue-equivalent material whi=
ch does not really exist and cannot be fabricated.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_no=
te-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> The ICRU sphere is a theoretical 30&nbsp;cm diameter "ti=
ssue equivalent" sphere consisting of a material with a density of 1 g=C2=
=B7cm<sup>=E2=88=923</sup> and a mass composition of 76.2% oxygen, 11.1% ca=
rbon, 10.1% hydrogen and 2.6% nitrogen. This material is specified to most =
closely approximate human tissue in its absorption properties. According to=
 the ICRP, the ICRU "sphere phantom" in most cases adequately approximates =
the human body as regards the scattering and attenuation of penetrating rad=
iation fields under consideration.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-13"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Thus radiation of a particular energy fluence will have roughly the same=
 energy deposition within the sphere as it would in the equivalent mass of =
human tissue.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-IAEACalibration_14-0" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-IAEACalibration-=
14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p>To allow for back-scattering and absorption of the human body, the "=
slab phantom" is used to represent the human torso for practical calibratio=
n of whole body dosimeters. The slab phantom is <span class=3D"nowrap">300 =
mm =C3=97 300 mm =C3=97 150 mm</span> depth to represent the human torso.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-IAEACalibration_14-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-IAEACalibration-14"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The joint ICRU/ICRP proposals outlined at the 3rd International Symp=
osium on Radiological Protection in October 2015 to change the definition o=
f operational quantities would not change the present use of calibration ph=
antoms or reference radiation fields.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-endo_8-1" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-endo=
-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Protection_quantities">Prot=
ection quantities</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Pro=
tection quantities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Protection quantities are calculated models, and are used as "limiting q=
uantities" to specify exposure limits to ensure, in the words of ICRP, "tha=
t the occurrence of stochastic health effects is kept below unacceptable le=
vels and that tissue reactions are avoided".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-1=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-IAEACalibration_14-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-IAEACalibration-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> These quantitie=
s cannot be measured in practice but their values are derived using models =
of external dose to internal organs of the human body, using <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computational_human_phantom" title=3D"Computatio=
nal human phantom">anthropomorphic phantoms</a>. These are 3D computational=
 models of the body which take into account a number of complex effects suc=
h as body self-shielding and internal scattering of radiation. The calculat=
ion starts with organ absorbed dose, and then applies radiation and tissue =
weighting factors.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>As protection quantities cannot practically be measured, operational=
 quantities must be used to relate them to practical radiation instrument a=
nd dosimeter responses.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Instrument_and_dosimetry_re=
sponse">Instrument and dosimetry response</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Instrument and dosimetry response"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>This is an actual reading obtained from such as an ambient dose <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_ray" title=3D"Gamma ray">gamma</a> =
monitor, or a personal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dosimeter" =
title=3D"Dosimeter">dosimeter</a>. Such instruments are calibrated using ra=
diation metrology techniques which will trace them to a national radiation =
standard, and thereby relate them to an operational quantity. The readings =
of instruments and dosimeters are used to prevent the uptake of excessive d=
ose and to provide records of dose uptake to satisfy radiation safety legis=
lation; such as in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UK" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"UK">UK</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Ionising_Radiations_Regulations_1999" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Ionising Radiations Regulations 1999">Ionising Radiations Regulations 1=
999</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Calculating_protection_dose=
_quantities">Calculating protection dose quantities</h2><span class=3D"mw-e=
ditsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;secti=
on=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Calculating protection dose quantities"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:SI_Radiation_dose_units.png" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/0/03/SI_Radiation_dose_units.png/960px-SI_Radiation_dose_units.png" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"550" height=3D"307" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"1142" data-file-height=3D"637"></a><figcaption>Graphic showi=
ng relationship of "protection dose" quantities in <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/SI" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI">SI</a> units</figca=
ption></figure>
<p>The sievert is used in external radiation protection for <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalent_dose" title=3D"Equivalent dose">equiva=
lent dose</a> (the external-source, whole-body exposure effects, in a unifo=
rm field), and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effective_dose_(rad=
iation)" title=3D"Effective dose (radiation)">effective dose</a> (which dep=
ends on the body parts irradiated).
</p><p>These dose quantities are weighted averages of absorbed dose designe=
d to be representative of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stoc=
hastic" title=3D"Stochastic">stochastic</a> health effects of radiation, an=
d use of the sievert implies that appropriate <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Relative_biological_effectiveness" title=3D"Relative biological=
 effectiveness">weighting factors</a> have been applied to the absorbed dos=
e measurement or calculation (expressed in grays).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ICRP1=
03_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siever=
t#cite_note-ICRP103-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The ICRP calculation provides two weighting factors to enable the ca=
lculation of protection quantities.
</p>
<dl><dd>&nbsp;1. The radiation factor <i>W</i><sub><i>R</i></sub>, which is=
 specific for radiation type <i>R</i> =E2=80=93 This is used in calculating=
 the equivalent dose <i>H</i><sub><i>T</i></sub> which can be for the whole=
 body or for individual organs.</dd>
<dd>&nbsp;2. The tissue weighting factor <i>W</i><sub><i>T</i></sub>, which=
 is specific for tissue type T being irradiated. This is used with <i>W</i>=
<sub><i>R</i></sub> to calculate the contributory organ doses to arrive at =
an effective dose <i>E</i> for non-uniform irradiation.</dd></dl>
<p>When a whole body is irradiated uniformly only the radiation weighting f=
actor <i>W</i><sub><i>R</i></sub> is used, and the effective dose equals th=
e whole body equivalent dose. But if the irradiation of a body is partial o=
r non-uniform the tissue factor <i>W</i><sub><i>T</i></sub> is used to calc=
ulate dose to each organ or tissue. These are then summed to obtain the eff=
ective dose. In the case of uniform irradiation of the human body, these su=
mmate to 1, but in the case of partial or non-uniform irradiation, they wil=
l summate to a lower value depending on the organs concerned; reflecting th=
e lower overall health effect. The calculation process is shown on the acco=
mpanying diagram. This approach calculates the biological risk contribution=
 to the whole body, taking into account complete or partial irradiation, an=
d the radiation type or types.
</p><p>The values of these weighting factors are conservatively chosen to b=
e greater than the bulk of experimental values observed for the most sensit=
ive cell types, based on averages of those obtained for the human populatio=
n.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Radiation_type_weighting_fa=
ctor_WR">Radiation type weighting factor <i>W</i><sub><i>R</i></sub></h3><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Radiation type weighting f=
actor WR"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</sp=
an></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalent_dose" tit=
le=3D"Equivalent dose">Equivalent dose</a></div>
<p>Since different radiation types have different biological effects for th=
e same deposited energy, a corrective <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Radiation_weighting_factor" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Radiation we=
ighting factor">radiation weighting factor</a> <i>W<sub>R</sub></i>, which =
is dependent on the radiation type and on the target tissue, is applied to =
convert the absorbed dose measured in the unit gray to determine the equiva=
lent dose. The result is given the unit sievert.
</p>
<table class=3D"wikitable" style=3D"float:right;">
<caption>Radiation weighting factors <i>W</i><sub><i>R</i></sub> <br> used =
to represent <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relative_biological_e=
ffectiveness" title=3D"Relative biological effectiveness">relative biologic=
al effectiveness</a><br> according to ICRP report 103<sup id=3D"cite_ref-IC=
RP103_2-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sie=
vert#cite_note-ICRP103-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</caption>
<tbody><tr>
<th>Radiation</th>
<th>Energy (<i>E</i>)</th>
