e-bracket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Operational_quantities_2">O=
perational quantities</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section=
: Operational quantities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The operational quantities are used in practical applications for monito=
ring and investigating external exposure situations. They are defined for p=
ractical operational measurements and assessment of doses in the body.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-ICRP_publication_103_-_Glossary_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-ICRP_publication_10=
3_-_Glossary-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> Three external operational dose quantities were =
devised to relate operational dosimeter and instrument measurements to the =
calculated protection quantities. Also devised were two phantoms, The ICRU =
"slab" and "sphere" phantoms which relate these quantities to incident radi=
ation quantities using the Q(L) calculation.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ambient_dose_equivalent">Am=
bient dose equivalent</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D14" title=3D"Edit section=
: Ambient dose equivalent"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>This is used for area monitoring of penetrating radiation and is usually=
 expressed as the quantity <i>H</i>*(10). This means the radiation is equiv=
alent to that found 10&nbsp;mm within the ICRU sphere phantom in the direct=
ion of origin of the field.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> An e=
xample of penetrating radiation is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Gamma_ray" title=3D"Gamma ray">gamma rays</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Directional_dose_equivalent=
">Directional dose equivalent</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D15" title=3D"Edit=
 section: Directional dose equivalent"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>This is used for monitoring of low penetrating radiation and is usually =
expressed as the quantity <i>H'</i>(0.07). This means the radiation is equi=
valent to that found at a depth of 0.07&nbsp;mm in the ICRU sphere phantom.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Examples of low penetrating rad=
iation are alpha particles, beta particles and low-energy photons. This dos=
e quantity is used for the determination of equivalent dose to such as the =
skin, lens of the eye.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In radi=
ological protection practice value of omega is usually not specified as the=
 dose is usually at a maximum at the point of interest.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Personal_dose_equivalent">P=
ersonal dose equivalent</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D16" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Personal dose equivalent"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>This is used for individual dose monitoring, such as with a personal dos=
imeter worn on the body. The recommended depth for assessment is 10&nbsp;mm=
 which gives the quantity <i>H</i><sub>p</sub>(10).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_n=
ote-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Proposals_for_changing_the_=
definition_of_protection_dose_quantities">Proposals for changing the defini=
tion of protection dose quantities</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span=
 class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/w/index.php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D=
"Edit section: Proposals for changing the definition of protection dose qua=
ntities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>In order to simplify the means of calculating operational quantities and=
 assist in the comprehension of radiation dose protection quantities, ICRP =
Committee 2 &amp; ICRU Report Committee 26 started in 2010 an examination o=
f different means of achieving this by dose coefficients related to Effecti=
ve Dose or Absorbed Dose.
</p><p>Specifically;
</p><p>1. For area monitoring of effective dose of whole body it would be:
</p>
<dl><dd><i>H</i> =3D =CE=A6 =C3=97 conversion coefficient</dd></dl>
<p>The driver for this is that <i>H</i><sup>=E2=88=97</sup>(10) is not a re=
asonable estimate of effective dose due to high energy photons, as a result=
 of the extension of particle types and energy ranges to be considered in I=
CRP report 116. This change would remove the need for the ICRU sphere and i=
ntroduce a new quantity called <i>E</i><sub>max</sub>.
</p><p>2. For individual monitoring, to measure deterministic effects on ey=
e lens and skin, it would be:
</p>
<dl><dd><i>D</i> =3D =CE=A6 =C3=97 conversion coefficient for absorbed dose=
.</dd></dl>
<p>The driver for this is the need to measure the deterministic effect, whi=
ch it is suggested, is more appropriate than stochastic effect. This would =
calculate equivalent dose quantities <i>H</i><sub>lens</sub> and <i>H</i><s=
ub>skin</sub>.
</p><p>This would remove the need for the ICRU Sphere and the Q-L function.=
 Any changes would replace ICRU report 51, and part of report 57.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-endo_8-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-endo-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A final draft report was issued in July 2017 by ICRU/ICRP for consul=
tation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Internal_dose_quantities">I=
nternal dose quantities</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Internal dose quantities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Committed_dose" titl=
e=3D"Committed dose">Committed dose</a></div>
<p>The sievert is used for human internal dose quantities in calculating <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Committed_dose" title=3D"Committed d=
ose">committed dose</a>. This is dose from radionuclides which have been in=
gested or inhaled into the human body, and thereby "committed" to irradiate=
 the body for a period of time. The concepts of calculating protection quan=
tities as described for external radiation applies, but as the source of ra=
diation is within the tissue of the body, the calculation of absorbed organ=
 dose uses different coefficients and irradiation mechanisms.
</p><p>The ICRP defines Committed effective dose, <span class=3D"mwe-math-e=
lement mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-m=
ath-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/=
1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle E(t)}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
