</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/65658b7b223af9e1acc877d848888ecdb4466560" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:0.84ex; height:2.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle t}">=
</span> is the integration time in years following the intake. The commitme=
nt period is taken to be 50 years for adults, and to age 70 years for child=
ren.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ICRP_publication_103_-_Glossary_6-2" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-ICRP_publi=
cation_103_-_Glossary-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The ICRP further states "For internal exposure, committed effective =
doses are generally determined from an assessment of the intakes of radionu=
clides from bioassay measurements or other quantities (e.g., activity retai=
ned in the body or in daily excreta). The radiation dose is determined from=
 the intake using recommended dose coefficients".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_not=
e-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A committed dose from an internal source is intended to carry the sa=
me effective risk as the same amount of equivalent dose applied uniformly t=
o the whole body from an external source, or the same amount of effective d=
ose applied to part of the body.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Health_effects">Health effe=
cts</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSievert&=
amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19" title=3D"Edit section: Health effects">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiobiology"=
 title=3D"Radiobiology">Radiobiology</a></div>
<p>Ionizing radiation has <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determin=
istic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Deterministic">deterministic</a> and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic" title=3D"Stochastic">s=
tochastic</a> effects on human health. Deterministic (acute tissue effect) =
events happen with certainty, with the resulting health conditions occurrin=
g in every individual who received the same high dose. <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stochastic" title=3D"Stochastic">Stochastic</a> (cance=
r induction and genetic) events are inherently <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Random" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Random">random</a>, wit=
h most individuals in a group failing to ever exhibit any <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Causal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Causal">caus=
al</a> negative health effects after exposure, while an indeterministic ran=
dom minority do, often with the resulting subtle negative health effects be=
ing observable only after large detailed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Epidemiology" title=3D"Epidemiology">epidemiology</a> studies.
</p><p>The use of the sievert implies that only stochastic effects are bein=
g considered, and to avoid confusion deterministic effects are conventional=
ly compared to values of absorbed dose expressed by the SI unit gray (Gy).
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Stochastic_effects">Stochas=
tic effects</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Sievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit section: Stochast=
ic effects"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>Stochastic effects are those that occur randomly, such as <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radiation-induced_cancer" title=3D"Radiation-ind=
uced cancer">radiation-induced cancer</a>. The consensus of nuclear regulat=
ors, governments and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UNSCEAR" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"UNSCEAR">UNSCEAR</a> is that the incidence o=
f cancers due to ionizing radiation can be modeled as increasing linearly w=
ith <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Effective_dose_(radiation)" ti=
tle=3D"Effective dose (radiation)">effective dose</a> at a rate of 5.5% per=
 sievert.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ICRP103_2-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-ICRP103-2"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This is=
 known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_no-threshold_=
model" title=3D"Linear no-threshold model">linear no-threshold model</a> (L=
NT model). Some argue that this LNT model is now outdated and should be rep=
laced with a threshold below which the body's natural cell processes repair=
 damage and/or replace damaged cells.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-28" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-28"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2=
8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There is general agreement=
 that the risk is much higher for infants and fetuses than adults, higher f=
or the middle-aged than for seniors, and higher for women than for men, tho=
ugh there is no quantitative consensus about this.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-peck_=
30-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#=
cite_note-peck-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-UNSCEAR_31-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-UNSCEAR=
-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Deterministic_effects">Dete=
rministic effects</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DSievert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D21" title=3D"Edit section: De=
terministic effects"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Effectofselfrepair.svg" class=3D"mw-file-desc=
ription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b=
/b3/Effectofselfrepair.svg/250px-Effectofselfrepair.svg.png" decoding=3D"as=
ync" width=3D"250" height=3D"186" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=
=3D"652" data-file-height=3D"486"></a><figcaption> This is a graph depictin=
g the effect of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dose_fractionation=
" title=3D"Dose fractionation">dose fractionation</a> on the ability of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gamma_rays" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Gamma rays">gamma rays</a> to cause cell death. The blue line is for =
cells which were not given a chance to recover; the radiation was delivered=
 in one session. The red line is for cells which were allowed to stand for =
a time and recover with the pause in delivery conferring <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Radioresistance" title=3D"Radioresistance">radioresi=
stance</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The deterministic (acute tissue damage) effects that can lead to <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acute_radiation_syndrome" title=3D"Acute =
radiation syndrome">acute radiation syndrome</a> only occur in the case of =
acute high doses (=E2=89=B3&nbsp;0.1&nbsp;Gy) and high dose rates (=E2=89=
=B3&nbsp;0.1&nbsp;Gy/h) and are conventionally not measured using the unit =
sievert, but use the unit gray (Gy).
A model of deterministic risk would require different weighting factors (no=
t yet established) than are used in the calculation of equivalent and effec=
tive dose.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"ICRP_dose_limits">ICRP dose=
 limits</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSiev=
ert&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D22" title=3D"Edit section: ICRP dose li=
mits"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span><=
/span></div>
<p>The ICRP recommends a number of limits for dose uptake in table 8 of rep=
ort 103. These limits are "situational", for planned, emergency and existin=
g situations. Within these situations, limits are given for the following g=
roups:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
31<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>Planned exposure =E2=80=93 limits given for occupational, medical a=
nd public</li>
<li>Emergency exposure =E2=80=93 limits given for occupational and public e=
xposure</li>
<li>Existing exposure =E2=80=93 All persons exposed</li></ul>
<p>For occupational exposure, the limit is 50&nbsp;mSv in a single year wit=
h a maximum of 100&nbsp;mSv in a consecutive five-year period, and for the =
public to an average of 1&nbsp;mSv (0.001&nbsp;Sv) of effective dose per ye=
ar, not including medical and occupational exposures.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-IC=
RP103_2-6" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sie=
vert#cite_note-ICRP103-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For comparison, natural radiation levels inside the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Capitol" title=3D"United States Capi=
tol">United States Capitol</a> are such that a human body would receive an =
additional dose rate of 0.85&nbsp;mSv/a, close to the regulatory limit, bec=
ause of the uranium content of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Granite" title=3D"Granite">granite</a> structure.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FUSRA=
P_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Siever=
t#cite_note-FUSRAP-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> According to the conservative ICRP mod=
el, someone who spent 20 years inside the capitol building would have an ex=
tra one in a thousand chance of getting cancer, over and above any other ex=
isting risk (calculated as: 20&nbsp;a=C2=B70.85&nbsp;mSv/a=C2=B70.001&nbsp;=
Sv/mSv=C2=B75.5%/Sv =E2=89=88 0.1%). However, that "existing risk" is much =
higher; an average American would have a 10% chance of getting cancer durin=
g this same 20-year period, even without any exposure to artificial radiati=
on (see natural <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epidemiology_of_ca=
ncer" title=3D"Epidemiology of cancer">Epidemiology of cancer</a> and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cancer_rates" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Cancer rates">cancer rates</a>).
</p>
