"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_ref-internal_40-3"><sup><i><b>d=
</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=3D"reference-text">Noted figures are =
dominated by a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Committed_dose" tit=
le=3D"Committed dose">committed dose</a> which gradually turned into effect=
ive dose over an extended period of time. Therefore the true acute dose mus=
t be lower, but standard dosimetry practice is to account committed doses a=
s acute in the year the radioisotopes are taken into the body.</span>
</li>
<li id=3D"cite_note-67"><span class=3D"mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_ref-67" aria-label=3D"Jump up" title=
=3D"Jump up">^</a></b></span> <span class=3D"reference-text">The dose rate =
received by air crews is highly dependent on the radiation weighting factor=
s chosen for protons and neutrons, which have changed over time and remain =
controversial.</span>
</li>
<li id=3D"cite_note-external-70"><span class=3D"mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_ref-external_70-0"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-accessibility-label">Jump up to: </span><sup><i><b>a</b></i></su=
p></a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_ref-external_7=
0-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=3D"reference-text">N=
oted figures exclude any committed dose from radioisotopes taken into the b=
ody. Therefore the total radiation dose would be higher unless respiratory =
protection was used.</span>
</li>
</ol></div></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSievert&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The sievert has its origin in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Roentgen_equivalent_man" title=3D"Roentgen equivalent man">r=C3=B6ntgen =
equivalent man</a> (rem) which was derived from <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/CGS_units" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"CGS units">CGS unit=
s</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Commissio=
n_on_Radiation_Units_and_Measurements" title=3D"International Commission on=
 Radiation Units and Measurements">International Commission on Radiation Un=
its and Measurements</a> (ICRU) promoted a switch to coherent SI units in t=
he 1970s,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-83" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-83"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>79<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and announced in 1976 =
that it planned to formulate a suitable unit for equivalent dose.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-84" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Sievert#cite_note-84"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>80<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The ICRP pre-empted the ICRU by introduci=
ng the sievert in 1977.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ICRP26_85-0" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-ICRP26-85"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>81<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>The sievert was adopted by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/International_Committee_for_Weights_and_Measures" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"International Committee for Weights and Measures">International C=
ommittee for Weights and Measures</a> (CIPM) in 1980, five years after adop=
ting the gray. The CIPM then issued an explanation in 1984, recommending wh=
en the sievert should be used as opposed to the gray. That explanation was =
updated in 2002 to bring it closer to the ICRP's definition of equivalent d=
ose, which had changed in 1990. Specifically, the ICRP had introduced equiv=
alent dose, renamed the quality factor (Q) to radiation weighting factor (W=
<sub>R</sub>), and dropped another weighting factor "N" in 1990. In 2002, t=
he CIPM similarly dropped the weighting factor "N" from their explanation b=
ut otherwise kept other old terminology and symbols. This explanation only =
appears in the appendix to the SI brochure and is not part of the definitio=
n of the sievert.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SI_86-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-SI-86"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>82<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Common_SI_usage">Common SI =
usage</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSiever=
t&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D27" title=3D"Edit section: Common SI usag=
e"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></sp=
an></div>
<p>The sievert is named after <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rolf=
_Maximilian_Sievert" title=3D"Rolf Maximilian Sievert">Rolf Maximilian Siev=
ert</a>. As with every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Internation=
al_System_of_Units" title=3D"International System of Units">SI</a> unit nam=
ed after a person, its symbol starts with an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Upper_case" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Upper case">upper cas=
e</a> letter (Sv), but when written in full, it follows the rules for capit=
alisation of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_noun" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Common noun">common noun</a>; i.e., <i>sievert</i=
> becomes capitalised at the beginning of a sentence and in titles but is o=
therwise in lower case.
</p><p>Frequently used <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_prefixes=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"SI prefixes">SI prefixes</a> are the milli=
sievert (1&nbsp;mSv =3D 0.001&nbsp;Sv) and microsievert (1&nbsp;=CE=BCSv =
=3D 0.000&nbsp;001&nbsp;Sv) and commonly used units for <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Time_derivative" title=3D"Time derivative">time deriv=
ative</a> or "dose rate" indications on instruments and warnings for radiol=
ogical protection are =CE=BCSv/h and mSv/h. Regulatory limits and chronic d=
oses are often given in units of mSv/a or Sv/a, where they are understood t=
o represent an average over the entire year. In many occupational scenarios=
, the hourly dose rate might fluctuate to levels thousands of times higher =
for a brief period of time, without infringing on the annual limits. The co=
nversion from hours to years varies because of leap years and exposure sche=
dules, but approximate conversions are:
</p>
<dl><dd>1&nbsp;mSv/h =3D 8.766&nbsp;Sv/a</dd>
<dd>114.1&nbsp;=CE=BCSv/h =3D 1&nbsp;Sv/a</dd></dl>
<p>Conversion from hourly rates to annual rates is further complicated by s=
easonal fluctuations in natural radiation, decay of artificial sources, and=
 intermittent proximity between humans and sources. The ICRP once adopted f=
ixed conversion for occupational exposure, although these have not appeared=
 in recent documents:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-87" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sievert#cite_note-87"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>83<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<dl><dd>8&nbsp;h =3D 1&nbsp;day</dd>
<dd>40&nbsp;h =3D 1&nbsp;week</dd>
<dd>50&nbsp;weeks =3D 1&nbsp;year</dd></dl>
<p>Therefore, for occupation exposures of that time period,
</p>
<dl><dd>1&nbsp;mSv/h =3D 2&nbsp;Sv/a</dd>
<dd>500&nbsp;=CE=BCSv/h =3D 1&nbsp;Sv/a</dd></dl>
